2 ostendisse potentium minos: i. e. probably the Emperor and his all-powerful friends such as Crispus and Marcellus. Vespasian was a humane ruler and not easily provoked to harah and unjust measures (cf. c. 8 20 patientissimus veri). Still, the hanishment of Helvidius Priscus and the expulsion of the Stoic and Cynic philoso phers (Cass. Dio 66, 13) were well calculated to arouse apprehensions for the safety of the bold poet who so frankly gave public expres- sion to his liberal convictions. The sentimenta put into Cato’s mouth cannot, however, as is generally supposed, have been directed against monarchical institutions as such, but were doubtless levelled against the political evils which had grown up under them, for Ma- ternus in c. 41 in perfect accord with similar utteranoes in the historical writings of Tacitus, (see Proleg. p. xxxvi), does not advo cate a return to a republican form of government hut, for reasons of expediency, sincerely acquiesces in the existing order of things, only deprecating the despotic abuse of monarchioal power. cf.
